The White House Press Secretary, Robert Gibbs, held a briefing on August 20, 2009. During the briefing, he announced that President Obama had spoken with King Abdullah of Jordan to discuss efforts to advance Middle East peace. They agreed on the need to launch Israeli-Palestinian negotiations and for all parties to take steps simultaneously to create a context for the negotiations to succeed. Gibbs also discussed the budget, the healthcare reform efforts, the release of the Lockerbie bomber, and the Afghan elections. He stated that decisions on women in combat and the color code alert system were left to the appropriate authorities.